{"id":"math/0411344","submitter":"Tom Leinster","authors":"Tom Leinster","title":"A general theory of self-similarity I","comments":"49 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS math.CT math.GN","license":null,"abstract":"  Consider a self-similar space X. A typical situation is that X looks like\nseveral copies of itself glued to several copies of another space Y, and Y\nlooks like several copies of itself glued to several copies of X, or the same\nkind of thing with more than two spaces. Thus, the self-similarity of X is\ndescribed by a system of simultaneous equations. Here I formalize this idea and\nthe notion of a `universal solution' of such a system. I determine exactly when\na system has a universal solution and, when one does exist, construct it.\n  A sequel (math.DS/0411345) contains further results and examples, and an\nintroductory article (math.DS/0411343) gives an overview.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Nov 2004 21:27:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
